 taken to Scotland in the 12th century by William <i>de Somerville</i>, a retainer of David, Earl of Huntingdon, who became King David I of Scotland.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Somacháin</b> (see   Summers  ) or <b>Mag Shamradháin</b> (see   Somers  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Siemer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Helmuth, Otto, Theresia.","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Siegmar</i>, composed of the elements <i>sigi</i> ‘victory’ + <i>mari</i>, <i>meri</i> ‘famous’."]},{"name":"Sommerville","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Somerville   1."]},{"name":"Summerville","meanings":["English, Scottish (Lanarkshire), and Irish: variant of   Somerville  . This form of the surname is particularly common in Ireland."]},{"name":"Simrell","meanings":["Scottish: perhaps related to the Ulster name<b>Sumeril</b>, a variant of   Somerville  ."]},{"name":"Summerfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’ + <i>feld</i> ‘field, open land’, denoting summer pasture or fields cultivated only in summer, such as Summerfield in Woodnesborough (Kent), Somerfield Court in Sellindge (Kent), and Summerfield in Marlborough (Wiltshire).","English: variant of   Somerville  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Sommerfeld  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas de Somerville of Carnwath was born in 1232, in Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland, his father, William de Somerville of Carnwath, was 49 and his mother, Lady Margaret of Newbigging, was 42. He married Mary Fraser in 1268, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1300, in his hometown, at the age of 68, and was buried in Melrose Abbey, Melrose, Scottish Borders, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1232–1300":"1232–1300","1238–1247":"1238–1247","1242–1296":"1242–1296","1234–1310":"1234–1310","1260–1330":"1260–1330","1291–1306":"1291–1306","1183–1215":"1183–1215","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","1330":"1330","1242":"1242","1296":"1296","1260":"1260","1183":"1183","1291":"1291","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1234":"1234","1310":"1310","1232":"1232","about 1300":"umbes 1300","Abt 1291":"umbes 1291","1306":"1306","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Melrose Abbey, Melrose, Scottish Borders, Scotland":"Melrose Abbey, Melrose, Scottish Borders, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Linton, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1232–1300":"1232–1300","1238–1247":"1238–1247","1242–1296":"1242–1296","1234–1310":"1234–1310","1260–1330":"1260–1330","1291–1306":"1291–1306","1183–1215":"1183–1215","1190–Female":"1190–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1330":"1330","1242":"1242","1296":"1296","1260":"1260","1183":"1183","1291":"1291","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1234":"1234","1310":"1310","1232":"1232","about 1300":"noin 1300","Abt 1291":"noin 1291","1306":"1306","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Melrose Abbey, Melrose, Scottish Borders, Scotland":"Melrose Abbey, Melrose, Scottish Borders, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland